        "text": "about\n\nTL;DR\n\nThis case study introduces Jacob, as the only design system lead, who bridged design team & engineering team, had led a full-spectrum mobile design system and established an effective way of collaboration across product & engineering, empowering 80 key stakeholders to bring value to 2.6m customers in UK for business success.\n\nInterestingly, we cannot take it for granted that people understand what's design system. Thus, Design System Academyâ¢ was also launched to educate teams with 'Atomic Design Methodology' by Brad F, and 'System in Systems' philosophy from Spotify, whichÂ effectively created a shared knowledge, reduced communication cost, and helped simplify engineering backlogs.\n\nAlso, Xero Go app has a 4.7/5.0 review in App Store.\n\nPhilosophy\n\nSystem in systems\n\nWhy this philosophy?\n\n- A governance model to distribute design systems across product lines in a company\n\n- Helped mobile team share and guardrail design assets, connecting between Xero foundation and local mobile design\n\n- Ensure our app has a unique UI and experience, and still under Xero's product ecosystem\n\nBy adopting it, we can sustain a connected user experience across platforms for digital accounting.\n\nmethodology / process\n\nAtomic Design\n\nHow did I bring team on the journey ð¤©\n\nImagine design system is a Harry Potter castle ð° ð° ð°, which is constructed from many Lego pieces assembled together.\n\n- a few Lego pieces (atom component) form a door (molecule component)\n\n- another set of Lego pieces (atom level) make up the main structure (organism component) of the castle (template component)\n\n- then come together to complete the entire Harry Potter castle (page component)\n\nSo the most fascinating part, also the key of building design system is to figure out 'what's reusable', so we say good-bye to doubling work on re-inventing wheels.\n\nDon't take it for granted, ever for designers âð»\n\nAtomic Design was a fair new knowledge for many engineers, even for some designers. Just because engineers often asked questions like should 'icon+text' on a button to be a (molecule) component to reuse? this took much of designer's energy, no efficiency at all ð­ð­ð­\n\nSo, I introduced Design System Academyâ¢ with 3 sessions to educate teams on Atomic Design Methodology by Brad F, then communication cost was reduced exponentially, since they understood how systems were built in Figma & codebase."
